              {
                "content": "> **Date**: March 29, 2026\n> **Launch window**: April 20 -- May 1, 2026 (two sequential weeks)\n> **Status**: DRAFT -- pending team review\n\n---\n\n## Milestone Definitions\n\n| Milestone | Definition |\n|-----------|------------|\n| **P0 Items Complete** | All must-have eng work done. Feature enabled for Factory's internal org for dogfooding/polish. |\n| **Release (100%)** | Feature enabled for all users. Individual orgs can be whitelisted between P0 and Release. |\n| **GTM Launch** | Blog post published, social media goes out, feature announced externally. |\n\n## Timeline Overview\n\n| Product | P0 Items Complete | Release (100%) | GTM Launch |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Code Review | Apr 10 | Apr 16 | Mon, Apr 20 |\n| Security Review | Apr 10 | Apr 16 | Wed, Apr 22 |\n| Deep Wiki | Apr 11 | Apr 17 | Fri, Apr 24 |\n| Automations Platform | Apr 14 | Apr 18 | Mon, Apr 27 |\n| Incident Response | Apr 16 | Apr 18 | Wed, Apr 29 |\n\n**Rationale**: Launch individual products first (Week 1), then the Automations Platform as the unifying layer (Week 2). This tells a narrative arc: \"Factory already reviews your code, secures your PRs, and documents your repos -- now you can orchestrate all of it with Automations.\"\n\n---\n\n## 1. Code Review\n\n### Current State\n- **Live in production.** GitHub App integration via `droid-review.yml` workflow.\n- CLI `/review` command with 4 presets (base-branch, uncommitted, commit, custom).\n- Two-pass review pipeline in droid-action: reviewer agent + validator agent.\n- 96.8% precision, 57% recall on 50-PR benchmark (PR #137 blog post draft exists).\n- ReviewBar in web diff viewer is mature (inline comments, autofix, send-to-droid).\n- No cost-to-quality analysis across models exists yet.\n\n### P0 Eng Work\n\n| Item | Description | Complexity | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Commit suggestions | Inline commit suggestions on review comments. | S | **DONE** |\n| Review as built-in skill | Move code review to a built-in CLI skill. | M | **IN PROGRESS** |\n| Cost-to-quality curve | Run the 50-PR benchmark with ALL models from `/models` menu: Claude Sonnet 4.5, Opus 4.5, Opus 4.6, GPT-5.1 Codex Max, GPT-5.2, GPT-5.2 Codex, GPT-5.3 Codex, Grok Code Fast 1, GLM 4.6, GLM 4.7, Gemini 3 Pro, Gemini 3 Flash, Claude Haiku 4.5. Plot cost ($) vs F1 score. | M | Not started |\n| Standard vs Deep Review tiers | Based on benchmark, define \"Standard Review\" (default fast/cheap model) and \"Deep Review\" (best-quality model) tiers. droid-action already supports `review_model` override -- document recommended defaults. | S | Not started |\n| Blog post finalization | Finalize PR #137 draft. Add cost-to-quality chart. Update competitor numbers if stale. | S | Draft exists |\n\n### GTM / Launch\n\n**Blog post**: \"Inside Factory's Review Research: Toward Fully Agentic Software Systems\"\n- Template: [PR #137](https://github.com/Factory-AI/factory-public-web/pull/137)\n- Key narrative: 96.8% precision benchmark results + cost-to-quality curve (unique in market -- no competitor publishes this)\n- Include concrete examples of bugs found that others missed (already in draft)\n\n**Novel marketing angles**:\n- **\"The Pareto frontier of AI code review\"**: Interactive chart showing cost vs quality across models. Let users see exactly what they're paying for.\n- **\"We publish our benchmarks. They don't.\"**: Transparency narrative -- open-source the benchmark dataset and methodology.\n- **Cost calculator**: Widget on landing page: \"How much would AI code review cost for your team?\" based on PR volume and model choice.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Security Review\n\n### Current State\n- **droid-action has full security review support**: `automatic_security_review` flag, `@droid security` command, STRIDE methodology, severity thresholds (`security_severity_threshold`), blocking on critical/high, team notifications (`security_notify_team`), scheduled scans.\n- `@droid security --full` does full-repo scans and creates PRs with reports.\n- Security skills auto-install from `Factory-AI/skills` repo (threat-model-generation, commit-security-scan, vulnerability-validation, security-review).\n- **What's missing from factory-mono**: No `/security-review` TUI command. The `install-github-app` flow only shows `droid` and `droid-review` workflows -- no `droid-security-review.yml` template.\n- `security-review-hub` repo exists for internal handling (enforcement deferred to 2026-04-11).\n\n### P0 Eng Work\n\n| Item | Description | Complexity | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| droid-action security review | `automatic_security_review` flag, `@droid security`, `@droid security --full`, STRIDE methodology, severity thresholds, blocking, team notifications, scheduled scans. | -- | **DONE** (in droid-action) |\n| Built-in security review skill | Add security review as a built-in CLI skill (threat modeling, commit scanning, vulnerability validation). | M | Not started |\n| `/security-review` TUI command | Add new slash command to CLI mirroring `/review` but using STRIDE-focused instructions. Presets: scan-PR, scan-staged, scan-branch, custom. | M | Not started |\n| `droid-security-review.yml` workflow template | Add security review workflow to `install-github-app` flow (`WorkflowSelectionScreen.tsx`, `constants.ts`). Uses `automatic_security_review: true`. | S | Not started |\n| Enable in `/install-github-app` | Add \"Droid Security Review\" as third workflow option alongside existing \"Droid\" and \"Droid Review\" in WorkflowSelectionScreen. | S | Not started |\n\n### GTM / Launch\n\n**Blog post**: \"Automated Security Review with STRIDE Methodology\"\n- Key narrative: Shift-left security that catches vulnerabilities before they ship. Not just a SAST scanner -- an AI agent that reasons about security using STRIDE.\n- Include example findings with severity levels, CWE references, and auto-generated patches.\n\n**Novel marketing angles**:\n- **\"Security review on every PR, not just quarterly audits\"**: Position as continuous security vs periodic pen testing.\n- **\"STRIDE-powered, not pattern-matched\"**: Differentiate from grep-based SAST tools (Semgrep, CodeQL) by emphasizing semantic reasoning.\n- **Blocking + notifications**: Highlight `REQUEST_CHANGES` on critical findings + team @mention -- integrates with existing security team workflows.\n- **Demo video**: Show a PR with a real vulnerability getting caught, blocked, and patched automatically.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Deep Wiki\n\n### Current State\n- **Mature UI** with solid design pass (card grid, reader, sidebar, Mermaid diagrams, TOC, version history, breadcrumbs).\n- Markdown-based rendering via `react-markdown` + `remark-gfm`. No raw HTML support.\n- No export functionality (PDF, markdown download).\n- Built-in Droid skill (`/wiki`), not a plugin. `wiki-upload` is a hidden CLI command.\n- No `/install-wiki` command. No manual refresh button in dashboard.\n- Content stored in Firestore. Generated via `/wiki` skill in Droid sessions.\n- Feature-flagged: `FactoryFeatureFlags.Wiki`.\n\n### P0 Eng Work\n\n| Item | Description | Complexity | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `/wiki` as built-in skill | Move from factory-plugins to built-in CLI skill, gated behind `FactoryFeatureFlags.Wiki`. | M | **IN PROGRESS** (PR #11522) |\n| `/install-wiki` as built-in skill | New TUI slash command that sets up a CI action (`factory-wiki-refresh.yml`) for auto-refresh on push to main. Creates workflow file and offers to open PR. Supports GitHub Actions and GitLab CI. | M | **IN PROGRESS** (PR #11522) |\n| Design pass / UI polish | Sidebar redesign (slide transitions, dual-mode repo groups, back navigation, text truncation), tile card redesign (Figma-spec matching, tooltips), ToC scroll fixes, version dropdown cleanup. | L | **IN PROGRESS** (PR #11369) |\n| Wiki refresh from dashboard | `useWikiRefresh` hook: modal with one-time vs recurring mode, local (CLI command) vs cloud (delegated session) execution, template picker for cloud, clickable success toasts linking to session. New session platform types: `WikiGeneration`, `WikiCISetup`. | L | **IN PROGRESS** (PR #11369) |\n| HTML rendering support | Update `WikiMarkdownRenderer` to support full HTML in wiki pages via `rehype-raw` with sanitization (DOMPurify). Enable interactive elements: collapsible sections, styled tables, embedded media. | M | Not started |\n| Interactive components | Timelines, architecture diagrams, study guides, pop quizzes, charts/heat maps. (FAC-17315) | L | Not started |\n| Incremental refresh | Don't regenerate wiki from scratch -- detect changed files and only regenerate affected pages. (FAC-17319) | M | Not started |\n| Improve depth | Increase wiki generation depth -- more detailed explanations, deeper code walkthroughs, richer cross-references between pages. | M | Not started |\n| Export functionality | Add export buttons to WikiReader: (1) Download as Markdown (.zip of all pages), (2) Download as PDF (single page or full wiki). Consider `@react-pdf/renderer` or server-side generation. | M | Not started |\n\n### GTM / Launch\n\n**Blog post**: \"Deep Wiki: Living Documentation That Writes Itself\"\n- Key narrative: Documentation that stays current because it regenerates on every push. Interactive pages with Mermaid diagrams, HTML elements, and full export.\n\n**Public wiki showcase website** (factory.ai/deep-wiki):\n- Modeled after [factory.ai/agent-readiness](https://factory.ai/agent-readiness)\n- 50+ open-source repos with pre-generated wikis (React, Next.js, Django, FastAPI, Prisma, Tailwind, etc.)\n- Search and filter by language, framework, stars\n- \"Request a wiki\" button -- users submit their repo URL and we generate it\n- Each wiki links to the interactive reader\n\n**Novel marketing angles**:\n- **\"The wiki that nobody has to write\"**: Developer pain point -- documentation is always out of date. Position Deep Wiki as the solution.\n- **Open-source gallery**: \"We generated wikis for 50 popular open-source projects. Browse them.\" -- drives organic traffic and demonstrates quality.\n- **\"Your README, but 100x deeper\"**: Show side-by-side of a README vs Deep Wiki for the same repo.\n- **Exportable**: \"Use it in onboarding, share it with non-technical stakeholders, embed it in your docs.\"\n\n---\n\n## 4. Automations Platform\n\n### Current State\n- **Mature, feature-flagged** (`automations`, default off), desktop-only.\n- Full sharing (private/org + fork). No templates or built-in automations.\n- Schedule-only triggers (daily/weekly/monthly/cron). No Slack/webhook triggers.\n- Computer automations behind `ManagedComputers` flag (cloud sandbox execution).\n- No CLI `/automations` command.\n- AI-assisted creation flow: setup assistant interviews user and scaffolds HEARTBEAT.md.\n- **Full Notion documentation exists**: PRD, Engineering Design Doc, Communication Plan, Example Automations.\n\n### Key PRD Insights (informing P0 scope)\n- **v1 non-goals per PRD**: Team-shared automations with access control, event-triggered automations (webhook/PR triggers), cloud-only execution. *Note: we are pulling cloud execution forward to P0 based on our decision.*\n- **\"Automations that evolve\"** is a differentiator to lean into: agent reads its own prompt, reads run history, proposes HEARTBEAT.md rewrites. UI can nudge \"this automation's failure rate increased -- want Droid to revise the prompt?\"\n- **Known limitations for support**: Machine must be on for daemon-based runs, in-memory state (history lost on daemon restart), no timezone config for cron.\n- **Comms Plan already drafted**: Audience segments, messaging (one-liner, elevator pitch, differentiators), 4-week rollout plan, content plan (docs, blog, changelog, in-app tooltip, example repo).\n- **5 example automations exist**: Weekly Dependency Audit, Daily Code Quality Metrics, Release Notes Generator, API Health Monitor, Security Scan -- these can seed the template gallery.\n\n### P0 Eng Work\n\n| Item | Description | Complexity | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Sharing (private/org + fork) | Toggle between private and organization visibility. Fork shared automations. | -- | **DONE** |\n| Template gallery | Build a template browser in the Create Automation modal. Seed with the 5 example automations from the Notion doc (Dependency Audit, Code Quality Metrics, Release Notes, API Health Monitor, Security Scan) plus product-specific templates (Code Review audit, Deep Wiki refresh, Agent Readiness report). Each template = a HEARTBEAT.md + description + category tag. | L | Not started (5 example HEARTBEAT.md templates already written in Notion) |\n| Design pass | Visual refinement: polish card grid layout, automation detail panel, create modal. Review with design team. | S | Not started |\n| Automations on cloud computers | Enable running automations in cloud sandboxes (E2B). Wire the existing `ComputerAutomations` UI to the backend v0 API. Remove `ManagedComputers` feature flag gate or add to automations page. | L | Not started |\n| Remove feature flag | Remove `FactoryFeatureFlags.Automations` gate. Make automations available to all users. | S | Not started |\n\n### P1 Eng Work (Post-Launch)\n\n| Item | Description | Complexity | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| CLI `/automations` command | Add `/automations` TUI slash command to list, run, pause, and create automations from the CLI. Requires daemon RPC bridge. | M | Not started |\n\n### GTM / Launch\n\n**Blog post**: \"Introducing Factory Automations: Your Engineering Team on Autopilot\"\n- Key narrative: Recurring AI agent sessions that handle the work your team never has time for. Code reviews, security scans, documentation, and custom workflows -- all running on a schedule.\n- Show the template gallery: \"Get started in 30 seconds with built-in templates.\"\n\n**Messaging from Comms Plan**:\n- One-liner: \"Factory Automations: scheduled AI agent tasks that run on autopilot.\"\n- Elevator pitch: \"Define recurring tasks -- dependency audits, security scans, code quality reports -- and your Droid runs them on a daily, weekly, or custom schedule.\"\n- Key differentiators: file-based (commit to git, review in PRs), stateful (memory persists across runs), visual (HTML dashboards), resilient (retry + degraded state).\n\n**Novel marketing angles**:\n- **\"Automations that evolve\"** (from PRD): Lean into the self-improving angle -- agent reads its own history and proposes prompt rewrites. \"Your automation gets smarter every time it runs.\" No competitor has this.\n- **\"What if your best engineer worked nights and weekends?\"**: Automations run on schedule, never forget, never get tired.\n- **Template gallery**: \"Start with our templates, customize them, share with your org.\" Seed with 5+ ready-to-use templates.\n- **\"From 0 to automated in 30 seconds\"**: Video showing template -> configure -> first run -> results -- entire flow under 30 seconds.\n- **Cloud computers**: \"Automations that run in the cloud, no laptop needed.\" Enterprise appeal -- set it and forget it.\n- **The unifying narrative**: \"You already use Factory for code review, security, and documentation. Now automate all of it.\" -- ties the individual product launches together.\n- **\"5 automations every developer should set up\"** (from Comms Plan content plan): Second blog post / listicle using the example automations.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Incident Response Automation\n\n### Current State\n- **Standalone Slack auto-run feature**, completely separate from Automations.\n- Backend-side (server webhook). Automations are daemon-side (desktop).\n- Triggered by bot messages (PagerDuty, Datadog, etc.) in configured Slack listening channels.\n- Creates headless droid sessions with \"Analyze this incident and suggest remediation steps.\"\n- Configured per-channel in Org Settings with `autoRun` toggle, custom prompts, workspace selection.\n- Feature flag: `SlackAutoRunHeadless`.\n\n### P0 Eng Work (Hybrid approach: UI unification now, runtime unification later)\n\n| Item | Description | Complexity | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Slack auto-run (server-side) | Bot message detection, headless session creation, custom prompts, channel settings. | -- | **DONE** |\n| Unified automations UI | Trigger type abstraction, automations tab integration (schedule + Slack side by side), create modal with trigger selector, channel config migration from Org Settings, backend bridge API. | L | Not started |\n| `/install-incident-response` skill | Interactive TUI skill that surveys the user on their incident workflow (alert sources, escalation policies, runbooks, Slack channels) and publishes a Slack automation configured to their responses. | M | Not started |\n\n### P1 Eng Work (Post-Launch)\n\n| Item | Description | Complexity | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Full runtime unification | Route Slack events through the daemon to unify with schedule-based automations. Single runtime for all trigger types. | L | Not started |\n\n### GTM / Launch\n\n**Blog post**: \"From Alert to Fix in Minutes: AI-Powered Incident Response\"\n- Key narrative: When PagerDuty fires, Factory is already investigating. Automated incident analysis, root cause identification, and remediation suggestions -- all in Slack where your team already works.\n\n**Novel marketing angles**:\n- **\"Your on-call copilot\"**: AI that wakes up with the alert, investigates before the human, and has a report ready.\n- **\"Slack-native incident response\"**: No new tools to learn, no context switching. Factory meets you where you already work.\n- **\"Triage at 3 AM, fix by 9 AM\"**: Story of an overnight incident where Factory had the analysis ready before the team woke up.\n- **Demo**: Show PagerDuty alert -> Slack message -> Factory auto-run -> analysis + suggested fix -- all within 2 minutes.\n\n---\n\n## GTM Calendar (Detailed)\n\n### Week 1: April 20--24 -- Individual Product Launches\n\n| Day | Product | Blog Post | Other |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mon Apr 20 | **Code Review** | \"Inside Factory's Review Research\" | Twitter thread: benchmark results. LinkedIn: enterprise angle. |\n| Tue Apr 21 | -- | Social amplification | Respond to engagement, share examples |\n| Wed Apr 22 | **Security Review** | \"Automated Security Review with STRIDE\" | Twitter thread: STRIDE demo. Security community outreach. |\n| Thu Apr 23 | -- | Social amplification | Developer-focused content, tutorials |\n| Fri Apr 24 | **Deep Wiki** | \"Living Documentation That Writes Itself\" | Launch factory.ai/deep-wiki showcase. Twitter thread: open-source wiki gallery. |\n\n### Week 2: April 27 -- May 1 -- Platform + Incident Response\n\n| Day | Product | Blog Post | Other |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mon Apr 27 | **Automations** | \"Your Engineering Team on Autopilot\" | Demo video. |\n| Tue Apr 28 | -- | Social amplification | Template showcase, \"automation of the week\" |\n| Wed Apr 29 | **Incident Response** | \"From Alert to Fix in Minutes\" | Twitter thread: incident demo. DevOps community outreach. |\n| Thu Apr 30 | -- | Recap post | \"5 launches in 10 days\" recap thread |\n| Fri May 1 | -- | -- | Collect feedback, plan iteration |\n\n### Cross-cutting GTM Tasks\n\n| Task | Timeline | Owner | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Write 5 blog posts | Apr 7--18 | TBD | See per-product GTM sections for key points |\n| Write \"5 automations every developer should set up\" listicle | Apr 14--18 | TBD | From Comms Plan; uses the 5 Notion example automations |\n| Build factory.ai/deep-wiki showcase page | Apr 7--18 | TBD | Model after factory.ai/agent-readiness |\n| Generate 50+ open-source wikis for showcase | Apr 7--18 | TBD | Prioritize by GitHub stars |\n| Record 5 demo videos (one per product) | Apr 14--18 | TBD | |\n| Prepare social media content | Apr 14--18 | TBD | Twitter threads, LinkedIn posts |\n| Update factory.ai product pages | Apr 14--18 | TBD | |\n| Docs: Getting started with Automations | Apr 7--14 | TBD | From Comms Plan |\n| Changelog entries for all 5 products | Apr 18 | TBD | From Comms Plan |\n| In-app tooltip / onboarding for Automations | Apr 14--18 | TBD | From Comms Plan |\n| Example automations repo (public) | Apr 7--14 | TBD | 5 HEARTBEAT.md templates already written in Notion |\n| Internal QA of all 5 products | Apr 14--18 | TBD | |\n| Run code review benchmark across all 14 models | Apr 1--10 | TBD | |\n\n---\n\n## Resolved Decisions\n\n| Question | Decision |\n|---|---|\n| Cloud computer automations | **P0** -- must have for launch. Stronger enterprise story (\"set and forget\"). |\n| CLI /automations command | **P1** -- ship post-launch. Automations are a desktop/dashboard feature for now. |\n| Deep Wiki \"move to core plugin\" | `/wiki` and `/install-wiki` being moved to built-in skills (PR #11522). No plugin marketplace needed. |\n| Benchmark models | All models from `/models` menu (14 models total). Full cost spectrum from Haiku to Opus. |\n| MTTR claims | Qualitative demo only. Avoid unsubstantiated metrics. Show PagerDuty -> analysis in 2 min. |\n| Rollout strategy | P0 complete -> internal org dogfooding -> whitelist individual orgs on request -> Release to 100% -> GTM launch. |\n| Product Hunt | No. Focus on blog + social. PH is a distraction from the core narrative. |\n| Pricing / model tiers | Standard Review (fast/cheap default) vs Deep Review (best-quality default). Users can override model via `review_model` in droid-action. Let benchmark results inform defaults. |\n\n## Remaining Open Questions\n\n1. **Cloud computer readiness** -- How mature is the E2B/cloud sandbox infrastructure? What's the gap between `ComputerAutomations` UI and a production-ready experience?\n2. **Design pass scope** -- Do we need design review sessions scheduled for each product? Who from design should be involved?\n3. **Blog post authors** -- Who writes each of the 5 blog posts? Can we parallelize across multiple writers?\n4. **Deep Wiki showcase repos** -- Which 50+ repos should we generate wikis for? Should we prioritize by GitHub stars, language diversity, or Factory customer repos?\n\n---\n\n## Risk Register\n\n| Risk | Impact | Likelihood | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cost-to-quality benchmark takes longer than expected | Delays Code Review launch | Medium | Start benchmark ASAP (Apr 1). Can launch without if needed and add later. |\n| HTML rendering in Deep Wiki introduces XSS vectors | Security vulnerability | Medium | Use DOMPurify for sanitization. Security review of implementation. |\n| Slack/Schedule trigger unification is more complex than expected | Delays Incident Response launch | Medium | Hybrid approach (UI-only unification) limits blast radius. Runtime unification is a fast-follow. |\n| Cloud computer automations not ready | Blocks a P0 item for Automations | High | Start early. If blocked, downgrade to P1 and launch desktop-only with \"cloud coming soon.\" |\n| Blog posts not ready in time | Delays GTM | Low | Start writing Apr 7. Use PR #137 as template. Parallelize across writers. |\n| 50+ wikis for showcase takes too long to generate | Reduces Deep Wiki launch impact | Low | Can launch with 20-30 and add more over time. Prioritize highest-star repos. |",
