Strategy` but doesn't update the corresponding error handling in `AuthMiddleware` -- something they would have missed without the wiki's explanation of how the pieces connect.\n\nAt Factory, a CLI engineer gets a bug report about wiki uploads failing for large repos. They've never touched the wiki backend. They open the Deep Wiki, navigate to the wiki system page, and see the full flow: CLI `wiki-upload` command -> `POST /api/v0/wiki` -> Firestore batch write -> page subcollection. The page notes the 200-page limit and 500KB-per-page constraint. They immediately realize the issue is hitting the Firestore batch size limit and know exactly where to look.\n\n### Living documentation via CI\n\nA tech lead at a company with 40 engineers is tired of the quarterly \"we should update our docs\" ritual that never sticks. Engineers write docs during a sprint, then the code changes and nobody touches the docs again. The team wiki in Notion is 60% outdated.\n\nThe tech lead runs `/install-wiki` in Factory. Droid asks which CI system they use (GitHub Actions or GitLab CI), then generates a workflow file that runs on every push to the default branch. The workflow triggers a Deep Wiki generation and uploads the result to Factory. The tech lead commits the CI config in a PR, it gets merged, and from that point on the wiki refreshes automatically.\n\nThree months later, a new engineer joins. They open the wiki and it reflects the codebase as of yesterday's merge to main. The architecture diagram shows the new microservice that was extracted last month. The \"Lore\" page documents the extraction as a major era in the project's history. The \"By the numbers\" page shows the codebase grew from 150k to 180k lines. Nobody maintained any of this -- the CI pipeline regenerated it all.\n\nAt Factory, the engineering team sets up `/install-wiki` on `factory-mono`. Every push to `dev` triggers a wiki refresh. When the team introduces a new package or renames a feature flag, the wiki picks it up on the next run. The \"Cleanup opportunities\" page surfaces 47 TODO comments, 3 unused exports, and 2 dependencies that haven't been updated in over a year. The team uses it as a lightweight maintenance backlog.\n\n## Goals\n\n1. Generate a comprehensive, navigable wiki from any codebase with a single command or button click.\n2. Produce documentation that covers the \"middle layer\" -- architecture, domain explanations, patterns, data flows -- not just API signatures.\n3. Include visual aids (Mermaid diagrams) for architecture and data flows where they help understanding.\n4. Version each wiki generation run so teams can see how the codebase evolved over time.\n5. Keep wikis fresh via CI integration that regenerates on every push to the default branch.\n6. Surface the wiki in the Factory web and desktop apps with a reader UI, table of contents, version history, and sidebar navigation.\n7. Keep everything file-based and inspectable -- the generated wiki is a directory of markdown files, not an opaque artifact.\n\n## The missing middle layer\n\nThe interesting thing about Deep Wiki is where it sits in the documentation spectrum.\n\nOn one end, you have **source code**. It's always accurate (it IS the system) but requires reading ability, context, and time to extract understanding. On the other end, you have **READMEs and hand-written docs**. They're easy to consume but go stale, cover only what the author thought to write about, and rarely explain how pieces connect across boundaries.\n\nDeep Wiki occupies the space between them. It reads the source code and produces the narrative that connects it -- the architecture overview that shows how 20 packages relate, the domain page that explains why the auth module is structured the way it is, the contribution guide that tells you the team's testing conventions. This is the documentation that every team wants but nobody writes, because it requires reading the entire codebase and keeping it updated as the code changes.\n\nThree properties make this work:\n\n1. **The agent reads everything.** A human writing docs reads the parts they know and skips the rest. The agent does a full structural scan plus a deep code scan, discovering features, patterns, and subsystems that even experienced engineers might not know exist. The \"Coverage cross-check\" in the generation pipeline reconciles top-down topic discovery with bottom-up directory enumeration to ensure nothing is silently omitted.\n\n2. **The output is regenerable.** Because the wiki is generated from source code, not maintained by hand, staleness is a function of how recently the pipeline ran -- not how motivated someone is to update docs. CI integration makes this automatic: push to main, wiki regenerates, docs match code. The drift between documentation and reality drops to zero.\n\n3. **Complexity scales the value.** A 500-line utility library doesn't need Deep Wiki -- the README is enough. A monorepo with 15 apps, 30 packages, and 300k lines of code is where Deep Wiki becomes indispensable. The agent produces a proportionally larger wiki, with more domain pages, more diagrams, and more cross-references. The bigger and more complex the codebase, the more value the wiki provides -- exactly where hand-written docs break down.\n\nThe growth path: team sets up Deep Wiki on their main repo -> CI regenerates on every push -> new hires use it to onboard -> existing engineers use it to navigate unfamiliar domains -> the wiki becomes the team's shared understanding of the codebase. Over time, as the agent improves, the wiki gets richer -- better diagrams, sharper explanations, more connections between subsystems -- without any human effort.\n\n## Non-goals (v1)\n\n- **Manual wiki editing** -- the wiki is fully generated from source code; users don't edit individual pages by hand.\n- **Cross-repo wikis** -- each wiki covers a single repository. Understanding how multiple repos relate is a future consideration.\n- **Wiki diffing** -- comparing two wiki versions side-by-side to see what changed. Version history lets you navigate between runs but doesn't show diffs.\n\nA note on manual editing: it's tempting to let users tweak generated pages, but it creates a maintenance problem. If the wiki regenerates on next push, manual edits are overwritten. If we try to merge manual edits with generated content, we inherit all the complexity of three-way merging. For v1, the wiki is a pure function of the source code. If the output is wrong, the fix is to improve the generation, not to hand-edit the output.\n\n## User experience\n\n### Generating a wiki\n\n**CLI:** User invokes the `/wiki` skill. Droid surveys the repository, plans the page structure, generates pages (with sub-agent delegation for parallelism), assembles the output, and uploads it to Factory. The user sees progress as pages are generated. When complete, Droid prints a link to the wiki in the Factory app.\n\n**Web/Desktop:** User navigates to the Wiki section and clicks a refresh button for a specific repository. Factory runs the generation remotely (via workspace or computer) and the wiki appears once complete.\n\n### Browsing a wiki\n\n**Web/Desktop:** The Wiki section has two views:\n\n- **Index page** -- a card grid of all repositories with wikis. Each card shows the repo name, page count, last updated time, and a freshness indicator. Users can search, filter (fresh/stale/no-wiki), and paginate.\n- **Reader page** -- a full markdown reader for a specific wiki run. The reader includes:\n  - A sidebar with the page tree, organized by section. Pages are collapsible by directory and highlight the active page.\n  - A floating table of contents for the current page, with active heading tracking as the user scrolls.\n  - Breadcrumb navigation showing the path from the wiki root to the current page.\n  - Previous/next page navigation at the bottom of each page.\n  - A version dropdown showing all historical wiki runs for the repo, each labeled with commit hash, branch, and date. Selecting a different version navigates to that run.\n  - Mermaid diagram rendering inline in the markdown.\n  - Internal cross-links between wiki pages, resolved to in-app navigation.\n\n### Keeping a wiki fresh\n\n**Manual:** User re-runs `/wiki` or clicks refresh in the web UI whenever they want an updated wiki.\n\n**CI (automated):** User runs `/install-wiki`, which generates a CI workflow file (GitHub Actions or GitLab CI) that triggers wiki generation on every push to the default branch. Once committed, the wiki stays current automatically. Each CI run creates a new wiki version, building up a version history over time.\n\n## What the wiki contains\n\nThe wiki is organized into three tiers of content:\n\n### Always-present pages\n\nEvery wiki includes these, in this order:\n\n- **Overview section** -- project overview (what it does, who uses it), system architecture with Mermaid diagrams, getting started guide (prerequisites, install, build, test, run), and a glossary of project-specific terms.\n- **By the numbers** -- a quantitative snapshot of the codebase: lines of code by language (with charts), file counts, activity trends, churn hotspots, complexity metrics. No individual contributor stats -- this page is about the codebase, not the people.\n- **Lore** -- the narrative history of the codebase. Major eras (e.g., \"The TypeScript Migration, Mar-Aug 2023\"), longest-standing features, deprecated features, major rewrites, and growth trajectory. Every event includes a date derived from git history.\n- **How to contribute** -- development workflow, testing conventions, debugging guides, coding patterns and conventions, and build/lint/CI tooling.\n\n### Domain deep-dives\n\nThe bulk of the wiki. The agent organizes the codebase into whatever lenses fit the repo's structure:\n\n- **Applications** -- if the repo ships multiple deployable units (e.g., a web app, a CLI, a backend API).\n- **Packages** -- if it's a monorepo with shared libraries.\n- **Systems** -- internal architectural components that don't map to a single app or package.\n- **Features** -- cross-cutting capabilities that span multiple systems (e.g., \"authentication\" touching frontend, backend, and CLI).\n- **Primitives** -- foundational domain objects that appear across 3+ systems (e.g., \"session\", \"user\", \"message\").\n\nEach domain page includes: purpose, directory layout, key abstractions (a table of important types with file paths), how it works (with Mermaid diagrams for data flows), integration points with other subsystems, and entry points for modification. Labels mirror the repo's own vocabulary -- if the repo calls things \"services\", the wiki calls them \"services.\"\n\n### Conditional sections\n\nIncluded based on what the repo actually contains:\n\n- **API reference** -- if the repo exposes REST, GraphQL, or WebSocket APIs.\n- **Deployment** -- if there's a non-trivial deployment process.\n- **Security** -- if there are meaningful trust boundaries.\n- **How to monitor** -- logging, metrics, tracing, and alerting (for repos that run as services).\n- **Background** -- design decisions, pitfalls, and migration context.\n- **Cleanup opportunities** -- dead code, TODO/FIXME comments, complexity hotspots, outdated dependencies. Only included if there's actual content to report.\n- **Maintainers** -- a table mapping subsystems to owners (from CODEOWNERS) and recent contributors (from git history).\n\n### Content principles\n\n- Every factual claim points to a source file. No vague \"the system handles X\" without a file reference.\n- Mermaid diagrams are used when they help explain architecture or data flows, not on every page.\n- Pages are cross-linked so readers can navigate without the sidebar.\n- Writing follows human documentation style -- plain language, no promotional tone, no AI-sounding patterns, no chatbot artifacts.\n\n## How generation works\n\nWiki generation follows a multi-phase pipeline:\n\n1. **Survey** -- the agent scans the repository structure (config files, entry points, directory layout) and then probes the code for features and capabilities that aren't visible from file names alone. The output is a comprehensive mental model of the codebase.\n\n2. **Plan** -- the agent designs the page tree: which sections to include, which lenses to use, which pages are critical (complex subsystems) vs. normal (straightforward components). Each page gets a content brief describing what to cover and which source files to read.\n\n3. **Foundation pages** -- the agent writes the overview, architecture, getting started, glossary, and coding patterns pages sequentially. These establish the shared vocabulary that all other pages reference.\n\n4. **Parallel generation** -- domain pages are delegated to sub-agents for depth and speed. Critical pages (complex subsystems) get a dedicated sub-agent each. Normal pages are batched in groups. Data pages (by-the-numbers, lore, fun-facts) run in parallel since they only need git history. Each sub-agent receives the survey context and its specific content brief, reads the relevant code, and writes its pages.\n\n5. **Remaining pages** -- contribution guides, conditional sections, and reference pages are generated after domain pages complete, since they cross-reference domain content.\n\n6. **Assembly** -- the agent audits cross-links between pages, generates the metadata file with page ordering, and verifies structural integrity.\n\n7. **Upload** -- the generated markdown files are uploaded to Factory's API, creating an immutable wiki run tied to a specific git commit and branch.\n\nThe entire pipeline produces a directory of markdown files with a `.wiki-meta.json` metadata file controlling page ordering in the sidebar. This directory can be inspected locally before upload, version-controlled, or generated in CI without human intervention.\n\n## Success metrics\n\n- **Adoption:** percentage of Factory users (or orgs) with at least one wiki generated.\n- **Freshness:** percentage of wikis with a generation run in the last 7 days (indicates CI adoption).\n- **Coverage:** average page count per wiki, correlated with repo size (bigger repos should produce more pages).\n- **Engagement:** wiki page views per user per week -- are engineers actually reading the wiki?\n- **Onboarding impact:** time-to-first-PR for new hires on teams using Deep Wiki vs. those without.\n- **CI adoption:** percentage of wikis that are refreshed via CI vs. manually.\n- **Retention:** percentage of wikis still being refreshed after 30 days.",
