            "new_str": "<table_of_contents color=\"gray\"/>\n## Overview\n\nDeep Wiki reads a codebase and generates a navigable set of documentation pages: architecture diagrams, domain deep-dives, contribution guides, codebase stats, and history. The output lives in Factory's web and desktop apps, is versioned per run, and stays fresh via CI.\n\n## Problem statement\n\nDocumentation falls into two buckets, and neither works:\n\n| What exists | What it covers | What it misses |\n|---|---|---|\n| READMEs | Setup, high-level intent | How subsystems connect, why things are built this way |\n| Auto-generated docs (JSDoc, rustdoc) | Function signatures | Architecture, data flows, patterns |\n| Hand-written architecture docs | Everything (briefly) | Accurate for ~1 week, then drifts |\n| Tribal knowledge | The real answers | Lives in heads, Slack, PRs. Leaves when people leave |\n\nThe gap is the **middle layer**: documentation that explains how pieces connect, what the patterns are, and where to start when you need to change something. It's the hardest to write and the first to go stale. Nobody writes it because it takes reading the entire codebase and keeping it updated as the code changes.\n\nDeep Wiki has an agent write that layer and re-run it on every push. Staleness becomes a function of pipeline freshness, not human motivation.\n\n## Target users\n\n- **Engineering teams** that need to understand each other's code\n- **Tech leads** who want living docs without assigning someone to maintain them\n- **New hires** who need architectural context and \"where to start\" guidance\n- **OSS maintainers** who want contributors to grok the project without hand-writing extensive docs\n\n## Core user journeys\n\n<details>\n<summary>**Onboarding a new engineer**</summary>\n\tA backend engineer joins a startup with a TypeScript monorepo (8 apps, 20 packages, 200k LOC). Day one, they open Factory's Wiki page and see the repo with a \"Fresh\" badge -- CI generated it two days ago.\n\n\tThey land on the overview: what the project does, a Mermaid architecture diagram, and \"Getting started\" with exact commands to clone, build, and run. Working dev environment in 20 minutes.\n\n\tOver the next few days they drill into domains. Assigned to the payments service, they open that page: purpose, directory layout, key types with file paths, a data flow diagram, integration points. The \"Entry points for modification\" section tells them where to start. Unfamiliar term? Glossary page. Testing conventions? \"How to contribute > Testing.\"\n\n\tA week in, they submit their first PR having understood the patterns before writing code.\n\n\t**At Factory:** a new CLI engineer opens the wiki for `factory-mono` and sees how `apps/cli` talks to `apps/backend` through `packages/common`, how the daemon protocol works, how skills are loaded. Instead of asking \"where does X live?\" for two weeks, they navigate the wiki.\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>**Investigating unfamiliar code**</summary>\n\tA frontend engineer reviews a PR touching `packages/auth/`, `apps/backend/src/middleware/`, and `apps/web/src/hooks/`. They understand the React hooks but not the backend.\n\n\tThey open Deep Wiki's auth page: token lifecycle, a sequence diagram of the refresh flow, a table of key types (`TokenService`, `AuthMiddleware`, `RefreshStrategy`) with file paths. The \"Integration points\" section lists what depends on auth and what breaks if the token format changes.\n\n\tTen minutes later they give a real review. They catch that the PR changes `RefreshStrategy` without updating error handling in `AuthMiddleware`.\n\n\t**At Factory:** a CLI engineer debugging wiki upload failures opens the wiki system page. They see the full chain: `wiki-upload` CLI command -> `POST /api/v0/wiki` -> Firestore batch write -> pages subcollection. The page notes the 200-page and 500KB-per-page limits. They find the root cause without ever having touched the backend.\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>**Living documentation via CI**</summary>\n\tA tech lead runs `/install-wiki`. Droid asks which CI system (GitHub Actions or GitLab CI), generates a workflow file that triggers wiki generation on every push to the default branch. The tech lead commits it in a PR.\n\n\tThree months later, a new engineer joins. The wiki reflects yesterday's merge to main. The architecture diagram shows a microservice extracted last month. The \"Lore\" page documents the extraction. The \"By the numbers\" page shows growth from 150k to 180k LOC. Nobody maintained any of this.\n\n\t**At Factory:** every push to `dev` triggers a wiki refresh. New packages, renamed feature flags, and deprecated modules are picked up automatically. The \"Cleanup opportunities\" page surfaces TODO comments, unused exports, and stale dependencies -- a lightweight maintenance backlog nobody had to write.\n</details>\n\n## Goals\n\n1. Generate a navigable wiki from any codebase with one command or button click\n2. Cover the middle layer -- architecture, domain explanations, patterns, data flows\n3. Use Mermaid diagrams for architecture and data flows where they help\n4. Version each run so teams can see how the codebase evolved\n5. Stay fresh via CI that regenerates on every push\n6. Surface in Factory web/desktop with reader UI, TOC, version history, sidebar nav\n7. Keep it file-based -- the wiki is a directory of markdown files, not an opaque artifact\n\n## The missing middle layer\n\n```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    A[\"Source code<br/><i>always accurate,<br/>hard to extract meaning</i>\"] --- B[\"Deep Wiki<br/><i>generated narrative<br/>that connects the code</i>\"] --- C[\"READMEs & hand-written docs<br/><i>easy to read,<br/>goes stale fast</i>\"]\n    style B fill:#2d6a4f,color:#fff\n```\n\nThree properties make this work:\n\n1. **The agent reads everything.** Humans write docs about the parts they know. The agent does a full structural scan plus a deep code scan, finding subsystems that even experienced engineers might not know about.\n2. **The output is regenerable.** Push to main, wiki regenerates, docs match code. Staleness drops to zero.\n3. **Complexity scales the value.** A 500-line library doesn't need this -- the README is enough. A monorepo with 15 apps and 300k LOC is where hand-written docs break down and Deep Wiki becomes worth it.\n\n## Non-goals (v1)\n\n- **Manual wiki editing** -- the wiki is a pure function of source code. If the output is wrong, improve generation, don't hand-edit. Manual edits would be overwritten on next CI run, and merging them with generated content means three-way merge complexity.\n- **Cross-repo wikis** -- one wiki per repo. Multi-repo understanding is future work.\n- **Wiki diffing** -- version history lets you browse past runs, but no side-by-side diff.\n\n## User experience\n\n### Generating\n\n| Surface | How |\n|---|---|\n| **CLI** | `/wiki` skill -- agent surveys, plans, generates pages via sub-agents, uploads. Prints a link when done. |\n| **Web/Desktop** | Click refresh on a repo card. Runs remotely via workspace or computer. |\n| **CI** | `/install-wiki` generates a GitHub Actions or GitLab CI workflow. Commits to repo. Auto-refreshes on every push. |\n\n### Browsing\n\nThe wiki UI has two views:\n\n**Index page:** card grid of repos with wikis. Search, filter (fresh/stale/no-wiki), paginate. Each card shows repo name, page count, last updated, freshness badge.\n\n**Reader page:**\n- Sidebar with collapsible page tree, active page highlighted\n- Floating table of contents with scroll-tracked active heading\n- Breadcrumbs and prev/next page navigation\n- Version dropdown (commit hash, branch, date per run)\n- Inline Mermaid rendering\n- Cross-links between wiki pages resolved to in-app navigation\n\n## What the wiki contains\n\n```\nwiki/\n├── overview/            # Always present\n│   ├── index.md         # What the project does, who uses it\n│   ├── architecture.md  # System diagrams (Mermaid)\n│   ├── getting-started  # Clone, build, test, run\n│   └── glossary.md      # Domain vocabulary\n├── by-the-numbers.md    # LOC, file counts, churn hotspots, complexity\n├── lore.md              # Codebase history, eras, rewrites, deprecated features\n├── how-to-contribute/   # Dev workflow, testing, debugging, patterns, tooling\n│\n├── <apps|packages|systems|features|primitives>/  # Domain lenses (at least one)\n│   ├── index.md         #   Each page: purpose, layout, key types,\n│   └── *.md             #   data flow diagrams, integration points\n│\n├── api/                 # Conditional -- only if the repo has APIs,\n├── deployment/          #   security boundaries, monitoring infra,\n├── security/            #   design decisions, or cleanup to report\n├── how-to-monitor/\n├── background/\n├── cleanup-opportunities/\n│\n├── reference/           # Config, data models, dependencies\n└── maintainers.md       # Subsystem -> owner mapping (CODEOWNERS + git history)\n```\n\n**Domain lenses** mirror the repo's vocabulary. At least one is required; most repos use 2-3. The agent picks which lenses apply based on what it finds in the code.\n\n**Content principles:** every claim references a source file. Diagrams earn their place by showing something hard to describe in text. Pages cross-link so readers can navigate without the sidebar. No promotional language, no AI-sounding patterns.\n\n## How generation works\n\n```mermaid\ngraph TD\n    A[Survey] -->|structural + deep code scan| B[Plan]\n    B -->|page tree, content briefs| C[Foundation pages]\n    C -->|overview, architecture,<br/>getting-started, glossary| D[Parallel generation]\n    D -->|critical pages: 1 sub-agent each<br/>normal pages: batched 3-5<br/>data pages: by-the-numbers, lore| E[Remaining pages]\n    E -->|how-to-contribute, conditionals,<br/>reference, maintainers| F[Assembly]\n    F -->|cross-link audit,<br/>.wiki-meta.json| G[Upload]\n    G -->|POST to Factory API| H[Immutable wiki run<br/>tied to commit + branch]\n```\n\nThe output is a directory of markdown files with a `.wiki-meta.json` controlling sidebar order. It can be inspected locally, version-controlled, or generated in CI.\n\n## Success metrics\n\n| Metric | What it measures |\n|---|---|\n| Adoption | % of orgs with at least one wiki |\n| Freshness | % of wikis refreshed in last 7 days |\n| Coverage | Avg page count per wiki (should correlate with repo size) |\n| Engagement | Wiki page views per user per week |\n| Onboarding impact | Time-to-first-PR with Deep Wiki vs. without |\n| CI adoption | % of wikis refreshed via CI vs. manually |\n| Retention | % of wikis still refreshed after 30 days |",
